observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our previous year’s audit recommendation that Management require the:

a.	Internal Audit Services (IAS) to implement COA Circular No. 2018-003, on the adoption of Internal Auditing Standards for the Philippine Public Sector (IASPPS) and Internal Control System for the Philippine Public Sector (ICSPPS) to improve effectiveness of governance, risk management and control process of the City;








b.	GSD to: 

Coordinate with IAS to address the noted weakness in internal control, and to come up with measures that will ensure timely recording of inventory movements in the property records and in the books to minimize the discrepancy between the RPCI and accounting records;






Coordinate with the City’s Accounting Department (CAD) for the conduct of thorough verification and reconciliation of the RPCI and accounting records to identify and resolve the nature and causes of variances, holding the designated supply officers/ custodians accountable and/or responsible for the discrepancies; and






Perform periodic reconciliation of property and accounting records to ensure that inventories are properly accounted for.

c. CAD to:

•	Coordinate with the GSD to ensure that inventory receipts and issuances are timely recorded in the books;



•	Ensure that all JVs drawn to recognize receipts and issuances of inventories are supported with valid and sufficient documentation;

•	Prepare and maintain an SLC for each inventory item and continually update the same to account for additions to and subtractions from inventory; and 

•	Prepare necessary adjustments to correct the balances of Inventory especially those with negative balances in the SLC.

All supply and property officers/custodians to:

•	Ensure that all inventory receipts and issuances are timely and completely recorded in the SC;


•	Make as part of their regular process on a monthly basis, the submission of copies of AIR/DR, RIS/RSMI, sales invoices/billings and other similar documents to the CAD for timely recording of inventories in the books of the City; and


•	Keep a complete and updated record of inventories under their custody

We recommended that the City Legal Department to pursue the immediate recovery of the 15% mobilization fee amounting to ₱44,683,381.95 through issuance of Final Notice of Demand to the contractor. Otherwise, upon failure of the Contractor to restitute the amount without further delay, the management may opt to consider the following:

a. Filing of appropriate legal actions for civil remedy to recoup the amount of P44.683 million possibly with additional interests and/or penalties in favor of the City Government. Likewise, avail all possible remedies for compensation such as attachment/lien on the property of the company or impleading the officers of the company in their personal capacity;

b. Demand/enforce the provision of bank guaranty/surety bond posted by the contractor upon receipt of advance payment for 15% mobilization fee, in case still valid/effective as of date; 

c. Revisit/review the terms and conditions of the contract if there is such a provision in handling conflicts/disputes between the contracting parties arising from termination for convenience; and 

d. Issue a Blacklisting Order disqualifying the contractor from participating in the bidding of all government projects during the period of disqualification, only if warranted by circumstances.

We recommended that Management direct the:
IC to-strictly comply with the guidelines and procedures in inventory taking provided under Item 6.2 of COA Circular No. 2020-006, to wit:
Complete the tagging of PPE counted with pre-numbered stickers;
State clearly in the Inventory Count Form (ICF), RPCPPE or equivalent inventory working papers the actual condition of the various PPE counted, such as in good condition, needing repair, unserviceable, obsolete, no longer needed etc., to serve as basis of the GSD in the preparation of the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP); and
Ensure that PPE Found at Station and Non-Existing/Missing PPE are labeled as such in the “Remarks” column of the ICF/RPCPPE to facilitate the preparation of the relevant reports by the GSD;
GSD and CAD to continue to coordinate and conduct reconciliation of the results of physical inventory and accounting records and of their respective Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards as well, and identify and address the nature and causes of the variance amounting to P731.690 million;
GSD to continue to comply with its responsibilities under Item 6.3.1 of the subject COA Circular, specifically as follows:
Ensure that all issuances of PPE items are covered with PAR and that these PARs are updated or renewed accordingly;
Prepare reports such as the List of PPE Found at Station, List of Non-Existing/Missing PPE and IIRUP for PPE described as such in the ICF/RPCPPE submitted by the IC, to enable the CAD to take up the necessary adjusting entries for these properties;
CAD to continue to comply with its responsibilities under Item 6.3.2 of the said Circular, specifically to record the necessary adjustments, after completion of proper reconciliation with GSD, including to recognize PPE found at station and set up corresponding receivables from concerned accountable officers for missing PPE to establish the correct balances of PPE and other affected accounts; and
GSD, CAD and other concerned offices to proceed with the procedures in the disposition of non-existing/missing PPE, including those without available record of accountability and accounting pursuant to Items 7.0 and 9.0 of COA Circular No. 2020-006, taking also into consideration the sunset provision in the Circular that the procedures could no longer be used to further derecognize missing properties and/or cleanse subsequent discrepancies or unreconciled balances in PPE accounts.

We reiterated our previous year’s audit recommendation that Management require the:
Internal Audit Services (IAS) to implement COA Circular 
No. 2018-003, on the adoption of IASPPS and ICSPPS to improve effectiveness of governance, risk management and control process of the City;
GSD to:
Coordinate with IAS to address the noted weakness in internal control, and to come up with measures that will ensure timely recording of inventory movements in the property records and in the books to minimize the discrepancy between the RPCI and accounting records;
Coordinate with the City Accounting Department (CAD) for the conduct of thorough verification and reconciliation of the RPCI and accounting records to identify and resolve the nature and causes of variances, holding the designated supply officers/custodians accountable and/or responsible for the discrepancies; and
Perform periodic reconciliation of property and accounting records to ensure that inventories are properly accounted for.
CAD to:
Coordinate with the GSD to ensure that inventory receipts and issuances are timely recorded in the books;
Ensure that all JEVs drawn to recognize receipts and issuances of inventories are supported with valid and sufficient documentation;
Prepare and maintain an SLC for each inventory item and continually update the same to account for additions to and subtractions from inventory; and
Prepare necessary adjustments to correct the balances of Inventory especially those with negative balances in the SLC.
All supply and property officers/custodians to:
Ensure that all inventory receipts and issuances are timely and completely recorded in the SC;
Make as part of their regular process on a monthly basis, the submission of copies of AIR/DR, RIS/RSMI, sales invoices/billings and other similar documents to the CAD for timely recording of inventories in the books of the City; and
Keep a complete and updated record of inventories under their custody.

We recommended that the City Legal Department pursue the immediate recovery of the 15 percent Mobilization Fee amounting to P44,683,381.95 through issuance of Final Notice of Demand to the contractor. Otherwise, upon failure of the Contractor to restitute the amount without further delay, the management may opt to consider the following:
Filing of appropriate legal actions for civil remedy to recoup the amount of P44.683 million possibly with additional interests and/or penalties in favor of the City Government. Likewise, avail all possible remedies for compensation such as attachment/lien on the property of the company or impleading the officers of the company in their personal capacity;
Demand/enforce the provision of bank guaranty/surety bond posted by the Contractor upon receipt of advance payment for 15 percent mobilization fee, in case still valid/effective as of date;
Revisit/review the terms and conditions of the contract if there is such a provision in handling conflicts/disputes between the contracting parties arising from termination for convenience; and
Issue a Blacklisting Order disqualifying the Contractor from participating in the bidding of all government projects during the period of disqualification, only if warranted by circumstances.

We recommended that the General Services Officer:
Develop a plan with specific deliverables and deadlines to expedite the full implementation of centralized warehousing. This will enable the City to optimize and/or fully achieve the benefits and advantages of centralized warehousing, which is to effectively and efficiently manage, adequately safeguard, and simplify the accounting and reporting of the supplies and properties of the City;
Established policies and procedures on centralized warehousing operation/ Centralized Warehousing Operations Manual to ensure effectiveness and efficiency of the centralized warehousing operations;
Stop using the newly constructed centralized warehouse costing P210,312,928.02 for the storage of unserviceable properties for disposal and functional/serviceable items that are not in use, to avoid further deterioration thereof;
Coordinate with the DEPW to promptly resolve and/or address the deficiencies or issues identified during the joint inspection on August 5, 2023, so that the centralized warehouse can be turned over to the GSD and proper maintenance thereof can commence; and
Strictly comply with the provisions of Sections 114 and 155 of COA Circular No. 92-386 and Section 490(b)(3) of RA No. 7160 to effectively and efficiently manage the City’s assets.

We recommended that Management direct the Human Resource Department Office (HRDO) to:

Ensure timely submission of updated information of City employees to GSIS, such as new salary rates, employment status, positions, and such other pertinent information that will take effect on the particular due month to minimize the occurrence of unmatched records;



Promptly resolve the discrepancies reflected in the Exception Reports generated from the eBCS through the submission of appropriate membership updating forms to the GSIS before the following month’s remittance;



Exercise due diligence in the performance of their duties to avoid the recurrence of over and under remittances of GSIS contributions and loan amortizations, and hold them liable for any interest and surcharges that the GSIS will impose; and



Henceforth, strictly implement Section 6 of R.A. No. 8291.

We recommended that Management direct the:
Internal Audit Department to implement COA Circular No. 2018-003, on the adoption of IASPPS and ICSPPS, to improve effectiveness of governance, risk management and control process of the City;
GSD, CAD and Inventory Committee to coordinate and conduct reconciliation of the results of physical inventory and accounting records; identify and address the nature and causes of variances; and hold responsible/ accountable the designated supply officers/custodians pursuant to Section 491 of GAAM, Volume I, and other existing laws, rules and regulations, and henceforth, keep up reconciled reports at all times;
The Inventory Committee to-
Prepare, in coordination with GSD, CAD and Internal Audit Department, and submit the PIP for approval of the City Mayor to ensure that the conduct of inventory is properly and adequately planned pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Submit a copy of the approved PIP to COA at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities;
Use temporary control stickers in the conduct of physical inventory and attach the same to the prominent and secured portion of the inventoried PPE for proper and easy identification;
Prepare the List of PPEs Found at Station to facilitate the recognition of PPE items not recorded in the books to establish reasonable basis to consider the same as property of the City;
Prepare the List of Non-Existing/Missing PPEs to facilitate the conduct of required procedures in the derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without established accountability;
Strictly comply with the guidelines and procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006 in order to come up with reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts presented in the City’s financial statements.
The GSD to-
Use pre-numbered property tags or control stickers to all PPE containing the information required under Section 5.7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 and to attach the same to the prominent and secured portions of the inventoried PPE for proper and easy identification;
Ensure that all issuances of PPE items are covered with PARs as prescribed under Section 5.6 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Renew/update issued PARs every three years after issuance or whenever there is a change in custodianship to establish proper accountability.
The CAD to:
Record adjustments, after completion of proper reconciliation with GSD, to establish the correct balances of PPE and other affected accounts; and
Strictly comply with COA Circular Nos. 2018-003 and 2020-006, and Sections 491, GAAM, Volume I.

We recommended that Management direct the HRDO to:
Come up with appropriate measures to facilitate prompt and accurate remittances to prevent the recurrence of under and over remittances of amount due;
Instruct those in-charge of monitoring and deducting PhilHealth premiums and contributions to carry out their duties with due diligence and hold them liable for any interests and surcharges that the PHIC will impose;
Refund the over-withheld PhilHealth contributions during the year totaling P13,237,604.36 to City employees; and
Henceforth, strictly implement Section 20 (b) of RA No. 9241 and PHIC Circular No. 2016-0034.

We recommended that Management direct the HRDO to:
Ensure timely submission of updated information of City employees to GSIS such as new salary rate, employment status, positions and such other pertinent information that will take effect on the particular due month to minimize the occurrence of unmatched records;
Promptly resolve discrepancies or unmatched records between the ERF and the EBF before the following month’s remittance to avoid further incurrence of penalties, interest and surcharges;
Exercise due diligence in the performance of their duties to avoid the recurrence of over and under remittances of GSIS contributions and loan amortizations, and hold them liable for any interest and surcharges that the GSIS will impose; and
Henceforth, strictly implement Sections 6 of RA No. 8291 on the timely collection and remittance of GSIS contributions.

We recommended that Management direct the HRDO to:
Implement measures to facilitate prompt and accurate remittances to prevent/address the recurrence of under and over remittances of amount due;
Promptly resolve discrepancies or unmatched records between the City and the HDMF before the following month’s remittance to avoid further incurrence of penalties, interest and surcharges;
Instruct those in-charge of monitoring and deducting PAG-IBIG premiums and contributions to carry out their duties with due diligence and hold them liable for any interests and surcharges that the HDMF will impose; and
Henceforth, strictly implement Section E, Paragraph 4 of HDMF Circular No. 275.

We recommended that the Management require: 

The Internal Audit Department to implement COA Circular No. 2018-003, on the adoption of Internal Auditing Standards for the Philippine Public Sector (IASPPS) and Internal Control System for the Philippine Public Sector (ICSPPS) to improve effectiveness of governance, risk management and control process of the City;







The General Services Department (GSD) to ensure that the conduct of inventory-taking is properly and adequately planned through the preparation of inventory plan to achieve valid, accurate, complete, and efficient physical inventory pursuant to the principles of sound ICS under COA Circular No. 2018-003;




GSD and CAD to -

Coordinate with each other to conduct a thorough verification and reconciliation of the RPCI and accounting records; identify and address the nature and causes of variances; and hold responsible/ accountable the designated supply officers/custodians pursuant to Section 491 of GAAM, Vol. I; 




Perform periodic reconciliation of property and accounting records to ensure that inventories are properly accounted for; and


Establish control measures that will ensure that all acquisitions and issuances of supplies and materials are timely recorded in the books to minimize the discrepancy between the RPCI and accounting records.







All supply and property officers/custodians to 

Make as part of their regular process, on a monthly basis, the submission of copies of AIR/DR, RIS/RSMI, sales invoices/billings and other similar documents to the CAD for timely recording of inventories in the books of the City; and


Keep a complete and updated record of inventories under their custody and submit the required inventory reports to CAD on a regular basis.





The CAD to:

Submit documents to support the adjustments made amounting to P699,448,188.63;







-	Record necessary adjustments only after completion of proper reconciliation with the GSD to establish the correct balances of Inventory and other affected accounts, with the presence of valid supporting documents;

- 	Regularly update SLCs and ensure that their balances reconcile with the SL/GL; and


- 	Strictly comply with Sections 111 of PD No. 1445, COA Circular No. 2018-003, Sections 491 GAAM, Vol. I, Sections 182, 187 to 189 of GAM for LGUs.

We recommended that the Management to direct the:

The Internal Audit Department to implement COA Circular No. 2018-003, on the adoption of IASPPS and ICSPPS to improve effectiveness of governance, risk management and control processes of the City;





The Inventory Committee to-

Prepare, in coordination with GSD, CAD and Internal Audit Department, and submit the PIP for approval of the City Mayor to ensure that the conduct of inventory is properly and adequately planned pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006;


Submit a copy of the approved PIP to COA at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities;





Use temporary control stickers in the conduct of physical inventory and attach the same to the prominent and secured portion of the inventoried PPE for proper and easy identification;




Prepare the List of PPEs Found at Station to facilitate the recognition of PPE items not recorded in the books to establish reasonable basis to consider the same as property of the City;

Prepare the List of Non-Existing/Missing PPEs to facilitate the conduct of required procedures in the derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without established accountability;





Prepare a consolidated RPCPPE per PPE classification using the prepared RPCPPE per Office/Department as working papers;

Strictly implement COA Circular No. 2020-006 in the conduct of inventory of PPE.




The GSD to-

Use pre-numbered property tags or control stickers to all PPE containing the information required under Section 5.7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 and to attach the same to the prominent and secured portions of the inventoried PPE for proper and easy identification;



Ensure that all issuances of PPE items are covered with PARs as prescribed under Section 5.6 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;


Renew/update issued PARs every three years after issuance or whenever there is a change in custodianship to establish proper accountability.

CAD, GSD and Inventory Committee to, henceforth, coordinate and conduct reconciliation of the results of physical inventory and GSD records/RCPPE; identify and address the nature and causes of variances; and hold responsible/ accountable the designated supply officers/custodians pursuant to Section 491 of GAAM, Vol. I, and other existing laws, rules and regulations;


The CAD to:

Record adjustments after completion of proper reconciliation with GSD to establish the correct balances of PPE and other affected accounts, with the presence of valid supporting documents; and

Strictly comply with COA Circular Nos. 2018-003 and 2020-006, and Sections 491, GAAM, Vol. I.

We recommended that the Management to:

Set-up effective and efficient controls over denied, returned and untimely filed claims such as but not limited to:

Coming up with policies detailing the procedural guidelines in the assessment, review and filing of claims to PHIC and defining the responsibilities of those in charge thereof including the imposition of appropriate sanctions for unjustified failure to properly discharge such duties; Such diligence has to be coupled with a quality review to ensure that claims are compliant, accurate, complete and filed in a timely manner;

Ensure that assigned personnel in the assessment, review and filing of claims exercise due diligence in the performance of their duties




Preparation of monthly monitoring report on the status of outstanding PHIC claims;


Preparation of evaluation report to identify the causes of denied, returned and untimely filed claims and the person/s responsible thereof; 


Strictly cause the patients to provide complete requirements upon discharge before deducting PHIC benefit from their total bill or account. Otherwise, cause the immediate payment or execution of promissory note;




Provide a separate ICD/RVS encoder in the Billing and Claims Section;




Provide adequate number of personal computers for the use of PHIC claims processors to increase work productivity; and


Reconcile the accounting records with that of the PHIC and make appropriate adjustments to eliminate overstatement of the Due from GOCCs – PHIC account.

We recommended that the Management direct the HRDO to:

Ensure timely submission of the updated information of City employees to GSIS such as new salary rate, employment status, positions and such other pertinent information that will take effect on the particular due month to minimize the occurrence of unmatched records;





Reconcile the discrepancies between the ERF and the EBF, and make representations with the GSIS to discuss the outcome of the reconciliation and the necessary actions that needs to be undertaken so that all overdue GSIS contributions and loan amortizations can be settled/remitted to avoid further incurrence of penalties, interest and surcharges;

Exercise due diligence in the performance of their duties to avoid the recurrence of over and under remittances of GSIS contributions and loan amortizations, and hold them liable for any interest and surcharges that the GSIS will impose; and




Strictly implement Sections 6 of RA No. 8291.

We recommended that Management:
Institute a well-defined collection system by way of policies and resolutions to enforce and ensure efficient collection of patients’ outstanding accounts which includes procedural guidelines from assessment of patients’ qualification in applying for installment payments up to monitoring, collection and reporting of outstanding accounts;
Exert collection efforts such as issuing demand letters to the delinquent patients to enforce immediate collection/settlement of the notes receivables;
Evaluate the collectability of receivables from PHIC based on factors such as aging of accounts, collection experience, identified doubtful accounts, etc. and set-up provisions for impairment; and
Evaluate dormant accounts, if any, for possible write-off in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005.

The City Mayor to: 

Create an appraisal committee who will work for the fair valuation of all lands without costs and require the Accounting Department to record them in the books and GSD to update the RPCPPE;  





Require the Accounting Department and GSD to collaborate in the review of prior years’ transactions concerning land account and completion of the reconciliation process. Consequently, record the necessary adjustment in the books in accordance with PPSAS 17;

Require the GSD and Accounting Department in coordination with Urban Development Department (UDD) and Assessment Department, to conduct ocular inspection of the lands and  note the exact location and actual use of properties without details or lack sufficient details in the accounting records and RPCPPE, to enable updating of records and reports; and

Direct the GSD to verify ownership of lands without titles with the Register of Deeds (RD) or Land Registration Authority (LRA). Accordingly, seek for the issuance of titles in the name of the City and/or undertake the necessary action on the results of verification with RD and LRA.

The Inventory Committee conduct a complete and thorough physical inventory of these PPE accounts together with the corresponding Land account and list of all City properties in the RPCPPE, prior to reconciliation with the accounting records;

The Accounting Department in coordination with GSD and DEPW should gather relevant documents and complete details of subject PPE items, and take up the necessary adjustments on depreciation and accumulated depreciation; and








The Accounting Department initiate the appraisal of subject properties, including Poblacion Public Market, if efforts to locate and retrieve previous records of the accounts proved futile, in order to determine the current fair values of the properties for subsequent adjustment of the PPE, depreciation expense and other related accounts.

The City Mayor to direct: 

The City Accountant to take up reversing entries restoring the balances of RPT and SET receivable accounts representing delinquent accounts aged ten years or more that have been written off in 2016;






The Finance Department to submit to the Sanggunian concerned the certified list of all real property tax delinquencies which remained uncollected or unpaid for at least one year and a statement of the reason or reasons for such non-collection or non-payment, on or before                 December 31st of the year immediately succeeding the year in which the delinquencies were incurred, with a request for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for collection, as required in Section 269 of R.A. 7160;

The Finance Department to apply administrative and judicial remedies provided for under R.A. 7160 that will enforce collection of delinquent taxes; and 





The City Assessor to make representation with the Registry of Deeds to inform the Assessment Department on a continuing basis of real property listed in its registry, to allow periodic updating of records of real properties in the assessment roll for any change in ownership or alienation, accompanied by copies of corresponding deeds of sale, donation or other forms of alienation.

The City Mayor and the Sangguniang Panlungsod to:

Restrain the UMak President from entering into agreements or contracts with the private institutions or organizations without the express approval of the Sangguniang Panlungsod. The City Mayor as Chairman of the Board of Regents, as authorized by the Sanggunian should represent the City in all its transaction and sign in behalf of the City, all contracts or agreements;

Regulate and control the actions of UMak officials such that these do not infringe the intent and primary purpose of its creation as stated in City Ordinance No. 99-126;

Initiate the review of any and all contracts of agreements entered into by the UMak President and other officials for and in behalf of the University, with private organizations to determine proprietary and legality of such action in relation to its mandate; and

Ensure that all contracts, agreements and related undertakings to be entered into or pursued by UMak involving government funds and property have the approval/concurrence of the Sangguniang Panlungsod.

The City Mayor to:

Require the DepEd Schools Division Superintendent to make a formal report regarding the IT equipment already lost, the persons accountable/ liable, and evaluation on the extent of their liability for the loss and the action taken by the Office for such loss. Also, require the DepEd Schools Division Superintendent to assume command responsibility for the proper safekeeping of equipment issued by the City;




Compel the school property custodians through the DepEd Schools Division Superintendent to account and make a report on the status of the 153 laptop computers and 53 study book tablets which were not presented during the physical inventory, and identify persons accountable for the loss;




Require school property custodians to turn over to the DepEd property custodian excess IT equipment so that these may be issued to other schools in need;

Require the DepEd Schools Division Superintendent to institute control measures for the property care and safekeeping of IT equipment;




Initiate recovery of the money value lost IT equipment and administrative and/or legal action against erring accountable DepEd personnel;








Require GSD that in the succeeding conduct of physical inventory, to include all relevant information in the RPCPPE  regarding existence and actual condition of the assets; and

Confer with DepEd officials, to require all retiring and resigning DepEd personnel assigned in the City to secure clearance from property accountability from GSD and City officials concerned prior to transfer to another government office or upon retirement, as a pre-requisite for the issuance of DepEd clearance. They should be required to return all City properties under their accountability as a requisite for the issuance of City clearance.

We have recommended that Management initiate the following courses of action:

Create a special committee to do the following:

Locate the original copies of titles or find out the reason why only photocopies are in the custody of the General Services Department (GSD);

Confirm with the Register of Deeds or Land Registration Authority the City’s ownership of land covered by the titles on hand;

Conduct an ocular inspection/ physical inventory of the land, take note of the exact location and actual use;

Initiate the determination or assignment of costs to titles acquired through a non-exchange transaction; and 

Furnish the City Accountant and the GSD with all information gathered.




Require the GSD to:

Maintain an inventory of all titles confirmed to be owned by the City;



Require a letter-request indicating therein the reason for every title to be taken out of the office;



Maintain a logbook for original titles taken out and require the person to whom the title was released to sign;



Keep the titles in a heavy duty vault;



Conduct an inventory of titles at least once a year; and 



See to it that the inventory reconciles with the accounting records.




Require the Accounting Department to:

Coordinate with the special committee and the GSD regarding the status of the titles and effect the necessary adjustment/s in accordance with PPSAS 17 and other applicable accounting standards;



Ensure that incidental cost are recorded or incorporated in the appropriate property item instead of recording them separately as they are incurred.



Initiate the move for Management to come up with a policy on the lots intended as relocation sites so that the appropriate accounting treatment can be made.
